<h2>Chapter 3: On-Page SEO for Law Firm Websites</h2>
<p>On-page SEO covers everything on the page itself. Title tags, meta descriptions, headers, content, images, and internal links. For law firms, on-page optimization also includes E-E-A-T signals that Google requires for YMYL content.</p>
<h3>Title Tags and Meta Descriptions for Legal Pages</h3>
<p>Every page on your site needs a unique title tag under 60 characters. Include your primary keyword and your city.</p>
<p><strong>Good title tag:</strong> "Personal Injury Lawyer in Dallas | Smith Law Firm"
<strong>Bad title tag:</strong> "Home | Smith &amp; Associates Law Firm"</p>
<p><a href="/blog/write-meta-descriptions/">Meta descriptions</a> should be 145 to 155 characters. Include the keyword, a benefit, and a call to action. "Injured in a car accident in Dallas? Our personal injury lawyers have recovered $50M+ for clients. Free consultation."</p>
<h3>Attorney Bio Pages That Build E-E-A-T</h3>
<p>Attorney bio pages are among the most important pages on a law firm website. Google's quality raters look at these pages to assess expertise and trustworthiness.</p>
<p>Every attorney bio page should include:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Full name and professional headshot</li>
<li>[ ] Bar admissions and license numbers</li>
<li>[ ] Education and certifications</li>
<li>[ ] Practice area specializations</li>
<li>[ ] Years of experience and notable case results</li>
<li>[ ] Published articles, speaking engagements, or media appearances</li>
<li>[ ] <a href="/blog/schema-markup-for-blog-posts/">Schema markup</a> for the Person entity</li>
</ul>
<p>Link each attorney bio to the practice area pages they support. This creates a clear expertise signal for Google. Add <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal links</a> from blog posts back to the attorney who authored them.</p>
<h3>Practice Area Pages That Rank</h3>
<p>Each practice area deserves its own dedicated page. Do not lump all services onto a single page. Google ranks specific pages for specific queries.</p>
<p>A strong practice area page includes:</p>
<ul>
<li>A clear H1 with the practice area and city</li>
<li>1,500 to 2,500 words of original content</li>
<li>An overview of the legal process</li>
<li>Common questions clients ask</li>
<li>Case results or settlement ranges (with disclaimers)</li>
<li>A consultation CTA above the fold and after each section</li>
<li><a href="/blog/blog-post-structure-seo/">Structured blog post layout</a> with logical header hierarchy</li>
</ul>
<p>Follow <a href="/glossary/on-page-seo/">on-page SEO best practices</a> for every practice area page. Optimize images with descriptive alt text. Use header tags (H2, H3) to create a scannable structure.</p>
